    &sup3;
    &sup3;   "Hailing from Richmond, Virginia, Municipal Waste are the
    &sup3;   reigning kings of the New Wave of Crossover. Municipal Waste
    &sup3;   deliver blazing fast, raw thrash-core in the tradition of
    &sup3;   DRI, Suicidal Tendencies, "Animosity"-era Corrosion Of
    &sup3;   Conformity, Nuclear Assault and Attitude Adjustment. All
    &sup3;   barely in their 20's, the members of Municipal Waste inject
    &sup3;   youthful energy and humor into a classic genre they were too
    &sup3;   young to catch the first time around.
    &sup3;
    &sup3;   With a self-titled EP on Amendment Records, an LP entitled
    &sup3;   "Waste 'Em All" on Six Weeks Records, and several splits and
    &sup3;   comps under their belts, Municipal Waste have quickly
    &sup3;   established themselves as the leaders of a fast-growing
    &sup3;   scene of bands resurrecting the spirit of the mid-80's
    &sup3;   Crossover scene.
    &sup3;
    &sup3;   Fast, furious, and funny, each of Municipal Waste's
    &sup3;   super-short songs is a memorable anthem to post-apocalyptic
    &sup3;   mutants, beer, thrash music, or all of the above. The band's
    &sup3;   dedication is deadly serious yet they are not afraid to
    &sup3;   bring the fun back into hardcore. Bashing out songs with
    &sup3;   such titles as "Thrashing's My Business And Business Is
    &sup3;   Good", "Thrash? Don't Mind If I Do", and "Drunk As Shit",
    &sup3;   (as well as a split EP whose songs were all based on Kurt
    &sup3;   Russell films), Muncipal Waste have earned themselves the
    &sup3;   tag of "party thrash".
    &sup3;
    &sup3;   Rumors of Municipal Waste's awesome live shows have spread
    &sup3;   from coast to coast and across the world; the band departs
    &sup3;   on their first European tour this month. Upon their return
    &sup3;   to the states, Municipal Waste will begin work on their
    &sup3;   Earache debut."
    &sup3;
